    "There is no place like Pinkand Whiteand/Opalfor Blue/Butte and I would write it/with Linus my loving dog/all Day & Landscape /Every Day, Oh Lord, I would/rain on and Writer with the rain/all Day & Landscapes, and write/all Blue & Loving all Night.\nPlot, character, style; these things matter, in a novel and a poem, only because people are so vain: they wish to be profound, not for divine inspiration but for possession. Writers, like most people, want to own books, because books are a proof, of sorts, of intellectual or moral property. They prove that the writer read the book and remembered what the writer said in her or his book on the same subject. Anyone who reads a book without keeping track of the plot and without asking questions never really reads the book at all, he or she only looks at the pictures. A sensitive reader may finish a book, notice who else has read it, and keep it under his or her pillow as one would a love letter: as an accumulation of dreams. Computers do not know, really, what they are doing while they are doing it; they only know what they have done when they finish doing it.\n",
