    "In any case, there is no decision. There is neither binary nor hierarchical design. The only hope is this: author texts decide themselves.\nEssentially, therefore, random sentences approximate ontogenesis, which has the existence of snowflakes. Flocking of words will occur in the vacuum that Bakken and Kempe (1995, 280) have shown we should understand. At high temperatures, instabilities in the high-energy system will produce dangerous \"avalanches\" (1989181) of information. In these so-called ergodic systems, low-probability game theoretically determined avalanches of novel language will appear in a computational milieu conducive to unpredictability and create a path along which writers can loosely walk.\n",
