    "But where is my own subject here? What have I been expressing by writing this book? You, the reader, cannot know it until you finish reading. Your Japanese proverb states that \"before the beads are counted, the rosary must end.\" Despite my knowledge of this, I still vulgarly go counting the beads first before finishing the prayer, don't I? And indeed even if I try not to count them until after the prayer is over, I do this from the mere shallow impulse to avoid seeming vacuous. I curse myself a thousand times as I write these lines, knowing full well that they have no bearing on what will come next.\nIf someone who has read me up to now were to express it in a single expression, it would be this: this book is \"a celebration of feebleness .\"\n",
